{'contentformat': 'text/x-wiki', 'contentmodel': 'wikitext', '*': '{{PokémonPrevNext/Head|type=Normal}}\n{{PokémonPrevNext/GO|species=Tauros}}\n{{PokémonPrevNext/Pokémon|type=Normal|prevnum=127|prev=Pinsir|nextnum=129|next=Magikarp|round=none}}\n{{PokémonPrevNext/Disambig|species=Tauros}}\n|}\n{{Pokémon Infobox\n|name=Tauros\n|jname=ケンタロス\n|jtranslit=Kentarosu\n|tmname=Kentauros\n|ndex=128\n|oldjdex=148\n|jdex=150\n|karea=Coastal\n|kdex=125\n|adex=137\n|fbrow=049\n|abrow=179\n|typebox=1\n|type1=Normal\n|category=Wild Bull\n|height-ftin=4\'07"\n|height-m=1.4\n|weight-lbs=194.9\n|weight-kg=88.4\n|abilityn=d\n|ability1=Intimidate\n|ability2=Anger Point\n|abilityd=Sheer Force\n|egggroupn=1\n|egggroup1=Field\n|eggcycles=20\n|evtotal=2\n|evat=1\n|evsp=1\n|expyield=172\n|oldexp=211\n|lv100exp=1,250,000\n|gendercode=0\n|color=Brown\n|catchrate=45\n|body=08\n|pokefordex=tauros\n|generation=1\n|friendship=70\n}}\n\'\'\'Tauros\'\'\' ([[List of Japanese Pokémon names|Japanese]]: \'\'\'ケンタロス\'\'\' \'\'Kentauros\'\') is a {{type|Normal}} {{OBP|Pokémon|species}} introduced in [[Generation I]].\n\nIt is not known to [[Evolution|evolve]] into or from any other Pokémon, but it is considered to be a counterpart of {{p|Miltank}}.\n\n==Biology==\nTauros is a quadruped, bovine Pokémon. It is covered in light brown fur with a thick, darker brown mane around the neck. It has a rounded muzzle with a dark brown nose, small, triangular eyes, three gray bumps running vertically down its forehead, and a pair of curved, gray horns grows from atop its head. Each of its three black tails has a tuft of fur on the end, and there is a single gray hoof on each foot. Tauros is a male-only species with no female counterpart.\n\nTauros is a violent, rowdy Pokémon that whips itself into a frenzy using its three tails. Once it starts charging, it is unable to stop or change course until it hits something. It lives and travels in herds on {{DL|List of Pokémon by habitat|Grassland Pokémon|plains and grasslands}}. It will lock horns with others of its kind, and the herd\'s protector takes pride in its battle-scarred horns. While still ferocious, Tauros are calmer in [[Alola]] than elsewhere, likely due to the region\'s climate. The practice of riding Tauros is believed to have started in Alola.\n\n==In the anime==\n===In the main series===\n[[File:Ash Tauros.png|thumb|300px|Tauros in the {{pkmn|anime}}]]\n====Major appearances====\n=====[[Ash\'s Tauros]]=====\n{{Ash}} {{pkmn2|caught}} a herd of 30 Tauros in [[EP035]], an episode that was [[Banned episodes|banned]] in multiple countries due to the prolific use of guns, leading to confusion for many as to how he obtained them. The first time Ash ever used any of his Tauros in a {{pkmn|battle}} was against {{OBP|Drake|Orange League}} of the [[Orange Archipelago|Orange Islands]] in \'\'[[EP111|Hello Pummelo]]\'\'.\n\n=====Other=====\nA {{pkmn|Trainer}}\'s Tauros appeared in \'\'[[EP099|The Mandarin Island Miss-Match]]\'\'. He battled {{Ash}}\'s Pokémon, easily defeating {{AP|Squirtle}} with {{m|Tackle}} before being knocked out by {{AP|Charizard}}\'s {{m|Flamethrower}}.\n\nTwo Tauros appeared in \'\'[[EP101|Get Along, Little Pokémon]]\'\', under the ownership of {{OBP|Ethan|EP101}}. He used them to pull his stagecoach as he traverses [[Mandarin Island South]].\n\nMultiple Tauros appeared in \'\'[[EP146|Tricks of the Trade]]\'\' in [[Palmpona]], including one under the ownership of [[Fernando]], a Trainer who managed to get ten consecutive victories in the tournament. Ash brought his from [[Professor Oak\'s Laboratory]] for this occasion as well, managing to defeat Fernando.\n\nA Trainer\'s Tauros appeared in \'\'[[EP166|Two Hits and a Miss]]\'\', where he had gone out of control. As a result, Ash had to use his {{AP|Bulbasaur}} to stop him.\n\nMultiple Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SM011|Young Kiawe Had a Farm!]]\'\', where they were among the Pokémon on [[Paniola Ranch]]. Two of them reappeared in \'\'[[SM030|The Ol\' Raise and Switch!]]\'\', where they fought with each other; and in \'\'[[SM033|Big Sky, Small Fry!]]\'\'. In \'\'[[SM070|The Young Flame Strikes Back!]]\'\', some of the Tauros attacked [[Kiawe\'s Marowak]], and one got annoyed at [[Ash\'s Poipole]] when he went to grab one of his tails.\n\nThree Poké Ride Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SM024|Alolan Open House!]]\'\', where they were stolen by [[Tupp]], [[Rapp]], and [[Zipp]] from children at the [[Pokémon School]].\n\nA Trainer\'s Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SM031|The Island Whisperer!]]\'\', where he attacked {{an|Kiawe}}\'s [[Poké Ride]] {{p|Charizard}}. The fight was later broken up by [[Olivia]]\'s {{p|Lycanroc}}, and Tauros was then calmed down by Olivia herself.\n\nA Poké Ride Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SM033|Big Sky, Small Fry!]]\'\', where [[Olivia]] used him to travel around [[Paniola Town]].\n\n====Minor appearances====\nMultiple Tauros debuted in \'\'[[EP033|The Flame Pokémon-athon!]]\'\', where they were seen at the Laramie Ranch. One was later seen among the Pokémon participating in the [[Big P Pokémon Race]].\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[EP047|A Chansey Operation]]\'\', where he was one of the injured Pokémon brought to the clinic.\n\nMultiple Tauros appeared in the opening sequence of \'\'[[M01|Mewtwo Strikes Back]]\'\', where they were among those captured by {{tc|Team Rocket Grunt}}s with the aid of {{OBP|Mewtwo|original series}}.\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[EP069|Lights, Camera, Quack-tion]]\'\' as part of the cast for the movie "{{DL|Movies in the Pokémon world|Pokémon in Love}}".\n\nMultiple Tauros appeared in a flashback in \'\'[[EP084|The Lost Lapras]]\'\'.\n\nMultiple Tauros appeared in \'\'[[M02|The Power of One]]\'\'.\n\nA Tauros appeared in the Japanese credits of \'\'[[PK04|Pikachu\'s Rescue Adventure]]\'\'.\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[EP169|Beauty and the Breeder]]\'\', under the ownership of a {{tc|Pokémon Breeder}} participating in [[Pokémon Beauty Contest|a Pokémon breeding competition]].\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[EP228|Extreme Pokémon!]]\'\', under the ownership of [[Mr. Shellby]]. He is used to pull his wagon so he can feed the Pokémon he is taking care of.\n\nMultiple Tauros appeared in \'\'[[EP233|A Tyrogue Full of Trouble]]\'\', where they went on a rampage after being startled by a troublesome {{p|Tyrogue}}.\n\nA Trainer\'s Tauros appeared in \'\'[[EP266|A Claim to Flame!]]\'\', where he battled in a qualifying match for the [[Silver Conference]].\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[AG011|A Bite to Remember]]\'\', under the care of {{OBP|Katrina|AG011}} while it was injured.\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[HS13|Celebi and Joy!]]\'\', under the ownership of [[Nick\'s father]]. He uses it for traveling.\n\nMultiple Tauros made brief cameo appearances in \'\'[[M07|Destiny Deoxys]]\'\'.\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[AG106|Beg, Burrow and Steal]]\'\'.\n\nMultiple Tauros made brief cameo appearances in \'\'[[M11|Giratina and the Sky Warrior]]\'\'.\n\nA Trainer\'s Tauros appeared in \'\'[[DP051|Glory Blaze!]]\'\' as a participant in the [[Hearthome City Tag Battle Competition]].\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[DP091|One Team, Two Team, Red Team, Blue Team!]]\'\', under the ownership of the [[Pokémon Summer Academy]]. It was used by one of the students in the first leg of the [[Pokémon Triathlon]].\n\nMultiple Tauros appeared in \'\'[[DP140|Historical Mystery Tour!]]\'\'. They were among the Pokémon {{an|Barry}} encountered in [[Xatu\'s Forest]].\n\nMultiple Tauros made cameo appearances in \'\'[[M12|Arceus and the Jewel of Life]]\'\'.\n\nMultiple Tauros appeared in \'\'[[Pokémon Ranger: Guardian Signs (anime special)#Part 1|Pokémon Ranger: Guardian Signs (Part 1)]]\'\', where they were captured by the [[Pokémon Pinchers]].\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[XY099|The Legend of the Ninja Hero!]]\'\', where he was used in the [[Ninja Village]].\n\nA Tauros appeared during a flashback in \'\'[[XYS05|The Legend of X, Y, and Z!]]\'\'.\n\nFour [[Poké Ride]] Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SM001|Alola to New Adventure!]]\'\'.\n\nTwo Poké Ride Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SM002|The Guardian\'s Challenge!]]\'\'.\n\nThree Poké Ride Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SM009|To Top a Totem!]]\'\', where a driver was using them to pull his cart.\n\nMultiple Tauros appeared in \'\'[[M20|I Choose You!]]\'\'.\n\nA Trainer\'s Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SM068|Real Life...Inquire Within!]]\'\', where Kiawe was cleaning him for work experience at the [[Pokémon Center]].\n\nA Trainer\'s Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SM090|Securing the Future!]]\'\', where he joined the rest of [[Alola]] in showering {{DL|Light trio (anime)|Necrozma}} with light so it could return to its {{DL|List of Pokémon with form differences|Necrozma|true form}}.\n\nA Trainer\'s Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SM129|Battle Royal 151!]]\'\', where it competed in the [[Battle Royal]] preliminary round of the [[Manalo Conference]] but ended up losing.\n\n====Pokédex entries====\n{{Animedexheader|Kanto}}\n{{Animedexbody|EP033|Tauros|Ash\'s Pokédex|Tauros, a Wild Bull Pokémon. When whipping itself with its three tails, its {{m|Tackle}} is a powerful destructive force.}}\n{{Animedexbody|EP035|Tauros|Ash\'s Pokédex|{{tt|Tauros. Its special attack is Tackle. Due to their docile nature, they won\'t attack without being assaulted first.|Translated from the Japanese version}}}}\n{{Animedexfooter/Pokémon|original|Kanto}}\n\n===In Pokémon Origins===\n[[File:Red Tauros PO.png|thumb|250px|Tauros in [[Pokémon Origins]]]]\n{{OBP|Red|Origins}}\'s Tauros appeared in \'\'[[PO04|File 4: Charizard]]\'\', where he was briefly shown battling {{p|Zapdos}} at the [[Kanto Power Plant]].\n{{-}}\n\n==In the manga==\n[[File:Ash Tauros EToP.png|thumb|150px|Tauros in [[The Electric Tale of Pikachu]]]]\n===In the Ash & Pikachu manga===\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SP08|Catch The Wobbuffet!!]]\'\'.\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[SP12|The Tyrogue\'s Thoughts]]\'\'.\n\n{{main|Ash\'s Tauros}}\n{{Ash}}\'s Tauros appears in \'\'[[SP16|One Half Of A Poké Ball]]\'\', where he was sent out to battle {{Gary}}\'s {{p|Nidoqueen}} and lost to her {{m|Hyper Beam}}.\n\n===In The Electric Tale of Pikachu manga===\n{{main|Ash\'s Tauros}}\n{{OBP|Ash Ketchum|EToP|Ash}} owns a Tauros in [[The Electric Tale of Pikachu]].\n\n===In the Pokémon Adventures manga===\n[[File:Tauler.png|thumb|left|150px|Tauros in [[Pokémon Adventures]]]]\nIn \'\'[[PS016|Tauros the Tyrant]]\'\', a Tauros, apparently captured in the {{safari|Kanto}}, was used as a mount by members of [[Team Rocket]]. By whipping his tails, he was able to control the Pokémon of the other {{tc|Team Rocket Grunt}}s, a method that {{adv|Green}} easily exploited by pushing it off a cliff and having [[Ditty]] mimic its appearance. He was later used in \'\'[[PS129|Great Girafarig]]\'\' to chase after Suicune, only to be defeated after Eusine\'s {{p|Jumpluff}} had {{m|Leech Seed}}ed him.\n\nIn \'\'[[PS108|Quilava Quandary]]\'\', the [[Day-Care Couple]] used a Tauros to help {{pkmn|training|train}} {{adv|Gold}}.\n\nA Tauros appeared in a fantasy in \'\'[[PS309|Moving Past Milotic]]\'\'.\n\n{{adv|Pearl}} {{pkmn2|caught}} a Tauros in \'\'[[PS403|Cleaning Up Grimer]]\'\', adding him to his main team and [[Nickname|nicknaming]] him Tauler.\n\nA Tauros appeared in \'\'[[PASM01|The Grand Entrance and Delivery Boy Sun]]\'\', called by {{adv|Sun}} via the [[Poké Ride|Ride Pager]], to help with deliveries in his job as a courier.\n\nA [[Poké Ride]] Tauros appeared in \'\'[[PASM04|The Decision and the Tournament of Six]]\'\' and \'\'[[PASM12|The Wild Full-Power Pose of Fire]]\'\'.\n\nTwo {{pkmn2|wild}} Tauros appeared in [[PASM23]], where they were seen in the [[Poni Wilds]].\n\n===In the Pokémon Gold & Silver: The Golden Boys manga===\nA Trainer\'s Tauros appeared in \'\'[[GB23|Let\'s Fight For The Future!!]]\'\'.\n\n===In the Pokémon Pocket Monsters manga===\n{{OBP|Red|Pocket Monsters}} catches a Tauros in \'\'[[PM014|Rampage At The Safari Zone?!]]\'\'.\n\n{{OBP|Professor Oak|Pocket Monsters}} is shown with one in \'\'[[PM040|Save the Pokémon Zoo!!]]\'\'.\n\n{{OBP|Giovanni|Pocket Monsters}} is seen with a Tauros in \'\'[[PM059|Good-Bye, Pikachu?!]]\'\'.\n\n===In the Pokémon Zensho manga===\n{{Zensho|Shigeru}} has a Tauros, which he caught in the Safari Zone.\n\n==In the TCG==\n{{main|Tauros (TCG)}}\n\n==In the TFG==\nOne Tauros figure has been released.\n\n* {{TFG|Next Quest}}: {{TFG ID|Next Quest|Tauros|36}}\n\n==Game data==\n===Pokédex entries===\n{{Dex/Header|type=normal}}\n{{Dex/Gen/1|gen=I|reg1=Kanto|num1=128}}\n{{Dex/Entry2|v=Red|v2=Blue|t2=FFF|entry=When it targets an enemy, it charges furiously while whipping its body with its long tails.}}\n{{Dex/Entry1|v=Yellow|entry=A rowdy Pokémon with a lot of stamina. Once running, it won\'t stop until it hits something.}}\n{{Dex/Entry1|v=Stadium|t=FFF|color=000|entry=Charges while whipping its hefty body with its tails. Although powerful, it can charge only in a straight line.}}\n|}\n|}\n{{Dex/Gen/1|gen=II|reg1=Johto|num1=148}}\n{{Dex/Entry1|v=Gold|entry=They fight each other by locking horns. The herd\'s protector takes pride in its battle-scarred horns.}}\n{{Dex/Entry1|v=Silver|entry=After heightening its will to fight by whipping itself with its three tails, it charges at full speed.}}\n{{Dex/Entry1|v=Crystal|entry=These violent Pokémon fight with other members of their herd in order to prove their strength.}}\n{{Dex/Entry1|v=Stadium 2|t=FFF|color=000|entry=They fight each other by locking horns. The herd\'s protector takes pride in its battle-scarred horns.}}\n|}\n|}\n{{Dex/Gen/2|gen=III|reg1=Hoenn|reg2=Kanto|num2=128}}\n{{Dex/Entry2|v=Ruby|v2=Sapphire|t=FFF|t2=FFF|entry=This Pokémon is not satisfied unless it is rampaging at all times. If there is no opponent for Tauros to battle, it will charge at thick trees and knock them down to calm itself.}}\n{{Dex/Entry1|v=Emerald|t=FFF|entry=It is not satisfied unless it is rampaging at all times. If there is no opponent for Tauros to battle, it will charge a